05107nam a22008535i 9780812298123DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122981237 a10.9783/97808122981232doi  a(DE-B1597)577468  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC328.6b.R475 2021 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a303.600aReverberations :bViolence Across Time and Space /ced. by Seda Altuğ, Alice von Bieberstein, Zerrin Özlem Biner, Yael Navaro. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe turn to the nonhuman in the humanities and social sciences has arguably been mobilized through a washing away of political violence, its histories, and its traces. Reverberations aims to redress this problem by methodologically and conceptually placing political violence and nonhuman entities side by side. The volume generates a new framework for the study of political violence and its protracted aftermath by attending, through innovative ethnographic and historical studies, to its distribution, extension, and endurance across time, space, materialities, and otherworldly dimensions, as well as its embodiment in subjectivities, discourses, and imaginations. Collectively, in the study of political violence, the contributions focus on human agencies and experiences in engagement with nonhuman entities such as objects, land, fields, houses, buildings, treasures, trees, spirits, saints, and prophets. In a variety of contexts, the scholars herein ask the crucial question: What can be learned about political violence by analyzing it in the terrain of relationality between human beings and nonhuman entities? How are things such as objects, spaces, natural phenomena, or spiritual beings entwined in histories of political violence? And vice versa—how are histories of political violence implicated in nonhuman things?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aPolitical violencevCase studies. 0aPolitical violencexEnvironmental aspects. 0aPolitical violence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aPolitical Science.1 aAltuğ, Seda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltuğ, Seda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaumann, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBieberstein, Alice von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiner, Zerrin Özlem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiner, Zerrin Özlem, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDawdy, Shannon Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvren, Erdem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagliardi, Connie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhayyat, Munira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Rosalind C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNapolitano, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavaro, Yael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavaro, Yael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avon Bieberstein, Alice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aÇaylı, Eray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978081229812342